Consider a classic cricket match that can be modeled as a Markov Chain. The states of the chain are the possible scores in a single play: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, and 6 runs, and the state transitions are the probabilities of moving from one score to another in a single play. 

Let's denote the transition matrix as P, where P(i, j) is the probability of moving from state i to state j. The student wants to find the steady-state probabilities, which are the probabilities of being in each state after a large number of plays.

Given the transition matrix P:

P = 
[0.5 0.2 0.1 0.1 0.05 0.05;
 0.1 0.5 0.1 0.1 0.1 0.1;
 0.05 0.1 0.6 0.05 0.1 0.1;
 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.7 0.05 0.1;
 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.7 0.1;
 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.05 0.75]

Find the steady-state vector π, which satisfies πP = π and the sum of all elements in π equals 1.
